Logistic Regression

The total of the responses for agreeing and disagreeing indicate a minimum of zero, median of 32, and a max of 593. The average was 68. Below a logistic regression analysis is also done and indicates both logistic coefficients to be negative values, meaning as the other coefficients increase in value the negative ones will decrease. The coefficients for education and female move linearly.

womensrole$total <- womensrole$agree + womensrole$disagree
summary(womensrole$total)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    0.00   10.00   32.00   68.36  100.50  593.00
womensrole_glm_1 <- glm(cbind(agree, disagree) ~ education + gender,
                        data = womensrole, family = binomial(link = "logit"))
round(coef(summary(womensrole_glm_1)), 3)
##              Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)

## education      -0.271      0.015 -17.560    0.000
## genderFemale   -0.011      0.084  -0.136    0.892

logit Posterior Distribution

Now a bayesian glm will be ran on the womens role dataset, it reveals that the bayesian model determines education to be an inverse coefficient. The model is testing the correlations between a response (agree or disagree) in relation to gender and education. The third predictor indicated in the output below is the intercept or coefficient.

library(rstanarm)
womensrole_bglm_1 <- stan_glm(cbind(agree, disagree) ~ education + gender,
                              data = womensrole,
                              family = binomial(link = "logit"), 
                              prior = student_t(df = 7), 
                              prior_intercept = student_t(df = 7),
                              chains = 4, cores = 2, seed = 12345, iter=3000)
womensrole_bglm_1

Prior Assumptions

Here we will explore the priors that we obtain from the generalized linear model. Exploring the prior distribution after we have established a posterior distribution will eliminate any motivations about the beliefs of a specific model parameter choice.

#Priors
prior_summary(womensrole_bglm_1, digits = 2)
## Priors for model 'womensrole_bglm_1' 
## ------
## Intercept (after predictors centered)
##  ~ student_t(df = 7, location = 0, scale = 10)
## 
## Coefficients
##  ~ student_t(df = [7,7], location = [0,0], scale = [2.5,2.5])
##      **adjusted scale = [0.41,2.50]
## ------
## See help('prior_summary.stanreg') for more details
priors<-prior_summary(womensrole_bglm_1, digits = 2)
names(priors)
## [1] "prior"           "prior_intercept"
priors$prior$scale
## [1] 2.5 2.5
priors$prior$adjusted_scale
## [1] 0.4079168 2.5000000

Bayesian Uncertainty Interval

The 95% confidence interval ranges from -0.3 to -0.24.This interval tells us that there is a 95% probability that an observation will be recorded in the distribution between -0.3 and -0.24.

ci95 <- posterior_interval(womensrole_bglm_1, prob = 0.95, pars = "education")
round(ci95, 2)
##           2.5% 97.5%
## education -0.3 -0.24

Post Estimation

Postestimation is useful to find outliers that are unwanted and can influence the model. Using the median absolute deviation (MAD) and the standard deviation of MAD can essentially be used to trim the dataset of unwanted observations that are not representative of the models distribution. For education an outlier would be considered anything outside of -0.2710813 +/- 0.0149786 and for genderFemale anything outside of -0.01020746 +/- 0.08546868 would be considered an outlier.

cbind(Median = coef(womensrole_bglm_1), MAD_SD = se(womensrole_bglm_1))
##                   Median     MAD_SD
## (Intercept)   2.51173148 0.18207448
## education    -0.27108130 0.01497860
## genderFemale -0.01020746 0.08546868

Traceplots

The traceplots indicate that the warm up period for the Monte Carlo generation of random values is somewhere around 500 observations. In addition, the education variables density is highest between -0.26 and -0.285 while the genderFemale variables greatest density is between 0.03 and -0.05.

#Traceplots
library(bayesplot)

plot(womensrole_bglm_1, plotfun = "trace") + ggtitle("Traceplots")

Autocorrelation Plots

The Autocorrelation of the education and genderFemale indicates that there is a small amount of error. This is good because if the model had excessive autocorrelation, the models specification may have a problem. From these plots we can conclude that the simulation is highly efficient because it has a low autocorrelation.

#ACF
plot(womensrole_bglm_1, plotfun = "acf") + ggtitle("Autocorrelation Plots")

Marginal Posterior Parameter Estimates

The marginal errors of our two parameters are small, indicating a weak influence by other parameters. This is usually a positive sign because we want to isolate parameters to have a small marginal error.

#we are plotting the 50% uncertainty interval (thick horizontal lines) and the 90% uncertainty interval (thin horizontal lines). In terms of interpretation, the 50% uncertainty interval identifies 
#where 50% of the marginal distribution lies for each parameter.
bayesplot_grid(
  plot(womensrole_bglm_1, plotfun = "intervals", prob = 0.5, prob_outer = 0.9, point_est = "median") + ggtitle("Marginal Posterior Parameter Estimates"),
  plot(womensrole_bglm_1, plotfun = "areas", prob = 0.5, prob_outer = 0.9, point_est = "median") + ggtitle("Marginal Posterior Parameter Estimates"),
  grid_args = list(ncol = 2)
)
## Warning: package 'bindrcpp' was built under R version 3.4.4

Marginal Posterior Parameter Distributions

The marginal posterior parameter distributions for the logit Monte Carlo Markov Chain (MCMC) model appear to be normalized with a density around what was seen in the traceplots. In addition, the Markov Chains had very little variation in their estimation.

#plot the histograms for each parameter (pooled across chains) and the empirical density of each parameter, respectively.
bayesplot_grid(
  plot(womensrole_bglm_1, plotfun = "hist") + ggtitle("Marginal Posterior Parameter Distributions"),
  plot(womensrole_bglm_1, plotfun = "dens_overlay") + ggtitle("Marginal Posterior Parameter Distributions"), 
  grid_args = list(nrow = 2)
)

cloglog Posterior Distribution

For this Bayesian generalized linear model I chose to explore the characteristics of the womensrole dataset using the binomial success probability parameter of cloglog, also known as the Complementary Log-Log Link Function. In addition, I also changed the number of iterations from 3000 to 100. This means that the warm-up period of the Monte Carlo simulation will be much shorter. From the output we see that the sample size that I chose is almost half of the effective sample size. Also,

library(rstanarm)
womensrole_bglm_1 <- stan_glm(cbind(agree, disagree) ~ education + gender,
                              data = womensrole,
                              family = binomial(link = "cloglog"), 
                              prior = student_t(df = 4), 
                              prior_intercept = student_t(df = 4),
                              chains = 4, cores = 2, seed = 12345, iter=100)

Traceplots

The traceplots that result from this Monte Carlo simulation has an extremely random distribution. It is very hard from glancing at the plots to tell where their highest density is located. The education varible appears to have somewhat of a higher density between -0.2 and -0.18 and the genderFemale seems to have a concentration of generated values around 0 and 0.1. The distributions are very random from my interpretation of the traceplots.

#Traceplots
library(bayesplot)
library(ggplot2)
color_scheme_set("mix-blue-pink")
plot(womensrole_bglm_1, plotfun = "trace") + ggtitle("Traceplots")

Autocorrelation Plots

Ignoring the lag component of the autocorrelation plots reveals increased variation and almost no trend of the plot increasing, decreasing or staying linear. The excessive autocorrelation of these variables indicates that there was a problem with the models specification. If the models specifications are not changed they will continue to be problematic and will result in low efficiency. One method to fix the models high autocorrelation is by thinning. Thinning the model by increasing the Monte Carlo Markov Chain sample size would most likely reduce the models excessive autocorrelation. My recommendation would be to remodel using a greater number of iterations.

#ACF
plot(womensrole_bglm_1, plotfun = "acf") + ggtitle("Autocorrelation Plots")

Marginal Posterior Parameter Estimates

After analyzing the output of the marginal posterior parameter estimates, the marginal error that characterizes this posterior distribution appears to be very wide. A wide marginal error is not ideal because it indicates correlation to parameters that are not of interest to our model.

#we are plotting the 50% uncertainty interval (thick horizontal lines) and the 90% uncertainty interval (thin horizontal lines). In terms of interpretation, the 50% uncertainty interval identifies 
#where 50% of the marginal distribution lies for each parameter.
bayesplot_grid(
  plot(womensrole_bglm_1, plotfun = "intervals", prob = 0.5, prob_outer = 0.9, point_est = "median") + ggtitle("Marginal Posterior Parameter Estimates"),
  plot(womensrole_bglm_1, plotfun = "areas", prob = 0.5, prob_outer = 0.9, point_est = "median") + ggtitle("Marginal Posterior Parameter Estimates"),
  grid_args = list(ncol = 2)
)

Marginal Posterior Parameter Distributions

The marginal posterior parameter distributions for the cloglog Monte Carlo Markov Chain (MCMC) model appear to be randomly distributed with a density that cannot easily be evaluated, as seen in the models traceplots. In addition, the Markov Chains had very high variation in their estimation. Consider running a higher number of iterations.

#plot the histograms for each parameter (pooled across chains) and the empirical density of each parameter, respectively.
bayesplot_grid(
  plot(womensrole_bglm_1, plotfun = "hist") + ggtitle("Marginal Posterior Parameter Distributions"),
  plot(womensrole_bglm_1, plotfun = "dens_overlay") + ggtitle("Marginal Posterior Parameter Distributions"), 
  grid_args = list(nrow = 2)
